WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:16.300
CHAPTER V of Meditations of Marcus Aurelius.

00:18.160 --> 00:24.700
The Meditations of Marcus Aurelius by Marcus Aurelius Antoninus.

00:25.540 --> 00:28.020
Translated by George Long.

00:28.820 --> 00:29.920
Chapter 5.

00:31.600 --> 00:37.440
In the morning, when thou risest unwillingly, let this thought be present.

00:38.220 --> 00:41.360
I am rising to the work of a human being.

00:42.040 --> 00:48.100
Why, then, am I dissatisfied if I am going to do the things for which I exist,

00:48.480 --> 00:50.600
and for which I was brought into the world?

00:51.580 --> 00:56.820
Or have I been made for this, to lie in the bedclothes and keep myself warm?

00:57.940 --> 00:59.280
But this is more pleasant.

01:00.220 --> 01:06.420
Dost thou exist, then, to take thy pleasure, and not at all for action or exertion?

01:07.080 --> 01:13.160
Dost thou not see the little plants, the little birds, the ants, the spiders, the bees,

01:13.880 --> 01:17.680
working together to put in order their several parts of the universe?

01:18.320 --> 01:21.740
And art thou unwilling to do the work of a human being?

01:22.480 --> 01:26.560
And dost thou not make haste to do that which is according to thy nature?

01:27.860 --> 01:30.680
But it is necessary to take rest also.

01:31.660 --> 01:33.080
It is necessary.

01:33.640 --> 01:37.100
However, nature has fixed bounds to this too.

01:37.500 --> 01:40.640
She has fixed bounds both to eating and drinking.

01:41.300 --> 01:45.980
And yet thou goest beyond these bounds, beyond what is sufficient.

01:46.980 --> 01:52.460
Yet in thy acts it is not so, but thou stoppest short of what thou canst do.

01:53.240 --> 01:55.520
So thou lovest not thyself.

01:55.920 --> 02:00.300
For if thou didst, thou wouldst love thy nature and her will.

02:01.340 --> 02:08.980
But those who love their several arts exhaust themselves in working at them, unwashed, and without food.

02:10.080 --> 02:15.740
But thou valuest thy known nature less than the turner values the turning art,

02:16.140 --> 02:20.940
or the dancer the dancing art, or the lover of money values his money,

02:21.600 --> 02:24.320
or the vainglorious man his little glory.

02:24.960 --> 02:29.120
And such men, when they have a violent affection to a thing,

02:29.680 --> 02:36.300
choose neither to eat nor to sleep, rather than to perfect the things which they care for.

02:37.020 --> 02:44.080
But are the acts which concern society more vile in thy eyes, and less worthy of thy labor?

02:45.780 --> 02:53.780
How easy it is to repel and to wipe away every impression which is troublesome or unsuitable,

02:53.940 --> 02:57.480
and immediately to be in all tranquillity.

02:59.120 --> 03:04.300
Judge every word and deed which are according to nature to be fit for thee,

03:04.740 --> 03:09.060
and be not diverted by the blame which follows from any people,

03:09.520 --> 03:10.900
nor by their words.

03:11.520 --> 03:17.540
But if a thing is good to be done or said, do not consider it unworthy of thee.

03:18.300 --> 03:25.000
For those persons have their peculiar leading principle, and follow their peculiar movement.

03:25.640 --> 03:29.580
Which things do not thou regard, but go straight on,

03:30.160 --> 03:36.440
following thy own nature and the common nature, and the way of both is one.

03:38.260 --> 03:44.420
I go through the things which happen according to nature, and I shall fall and rest,

03:44.880 --> 03:49.800
breathing out my breath into that element out of which I daily draw it in,

03:49.800 --> 03:54.900
and falling upon that earth out of which my father collected the seed,

03:55.480 --> 03:58.800
and my mother the blood, and my nurse the milk,

03:59.460 --> 04:04.460
out of which during so many years I have been supplied with food and drink,

04:05.060 --> 04:10.360
which bears me when I tread on it and abuse it for so many purposes.

04:12.120 --> 04:16.460
Thou sayest, men cannot admire the sharpness of thy wits.

04:17.140 --> 04:21.940
Be it so, but there are many other things of which thou canst not say,

04:22.320 --> 04:24.620
I am not formed for them by nature.

04:25.780 --> 04:29.860
Show those qualities, then, which are altogether in thy power,

04:30.540 --> 04:36.620
sincerity, gravity, endurance of labour, aversion to pleasure,

04:37.400 --> 04:43.940
contentment with thy portion and with few things, benevolence, frankness,

04:44.450 --> 04:49.640
no love of superfluity, freedom from trifling magnanimity.

04:50.480 --> 04:55.460
Dost thou not see how many qualities thou art immediately able to exhibit,

04:56.040 --> 05:00.640
in which there is no excuse of natural incapacity and unfitness,

05:01.220 --> 05:05.580
and yet thou still remainest voluntarily below the mark?

05:06.280 --> 05:10.840
Or art thou compelled through being defectively furnished by nature

05:10.840 --> 05:17.800
to murmur and to be stingy and to flatter and to find fault with thy poor body,

05:18.660 --> 05:25.080
and to try to please men and to make great display and to be restless in thy mind?

05:26.260 --> 05:31.960
No, by the gods, but thou mightest have been delivered from these things long ago.

05:33.020 --> 05:39.920
Only if in truth thou canst be charged with being rather slow and dull of comprehension,

05:39.920 --> 05:43.760
thou must exert thyself about this also,

05:44.140 --> 05:48.620
not neglecting it nor yet taking pleasure in thy dullness.

05:51.320 --> 05:54.380
One man, when he has done a service to another,

05:54.840 --> 05:59.120
is ready to set it down to his account as a favour conferred.

05:59.620 --> 06:06.340
Another is not ready to do this, but still in his own mind he thinks of the man as his debtor,

06:06.520 --> 06:08.400
and he knows what he has done.

06:09.160 --> 06:13.200
A third, in a manner, does not even know what he has done,

06:13.860 --> 06:16.680
but he is like a vine which has produced grapes,

06:17.180 --> 06:21.680
and seeks for nothing more after it has once produced its proper fruit.

06:22.420 --> 06:27.360
As a horse when he has run, a dog when he has tracked the game,

06:28.080 --> 06:34.160
a bee when it has made the honey, so a man when he has done a good act

06:34.160 --> 06:37.580
does not call out for others to come and see,

06:37.580 --> 06:40.280
but he goes on to another act,

06:40.800 --> 06:44.760
as a vine goes on to produce again the grapes in season.

06:46.140 --> 06:52.180
Must a man then be one of these who in a manner act thus without observing it?

06:52.920 --> 06:56.360
Yes, but this very thing is necessary,

06:56.700 --> 06:59.100
the observation of what a man is doing,

06:59.760 --> 07:04.140
for it may be said it is characteristic of the social animal

07:04.140 --> 07:07.820
to perceive that he is working in a social manner,

07:08.460 --> 07:12.840
and indeed to wish that his social partner also should perceive it.

07:14.200 --> 07:20.120
It is true what thou sayest, but thou dost not rightly understand what is now said,

07:20.940 --> 07:25.560
and for this reason thou wilt become one of those of whom I spoke before,

07:26.340 --> 07:30.180
for even they are misled by a certain show of reason.

07:31.130 --> 07:34.880
But if thou wilt choose to understand the meaning of what is said,

07:35.680 --> 07:40.760
do not fear that for this reason thou wilt omit any social act.

07:43.520 --> 07:45.720
A Prayer of the Athenians

07:46.520 --> 07:49.480
Rain, rain, O Dears Zeus,

07:50.160 --> 07:54.280
Down on the ploughed fields of the Athenians and on the plains.

07:55.280 --> 07:57.900
In truth we ought not to pray at all,

07:57.900 --> 08:02.540
or we ought to pray in this simple and noble fashion.

08:04.480 --> 08:11.420
Just as we must understand when it is said that Aesculapius prescribed to this man horse exercise,

08:12.020 --> 08:15.440
or bathing in cold water, or going without shoes,

08:16.300 --> 08:23.560
so we must understand it when it is said that the nature of the universe prescribed to this man

08:23.560 --> 08:28.580
disease, or mutilation, or loss, or anything else of the kind.

08:29.620 --> 08:33.800
For in the first case prescribed means something like this.

08:34.560 --> 08:39.800
He prescribed this for this man as a thing adapted to procure health,

08:40.620 --> 08:47.300
and in the second case it means that which happens to or suits every man

08:47.300 --> 08:51.700
is fixed in a manner for him suitably to his destiny.

08:52.660 --> 08:57.580
For this is what we mean when we say that things are suitable to us,

08:58.020 --> 09:02.500
as the workmen say of squared stones in walls or the pyramids,

09:02.800 --> 09:07.600
that they are suitable when they fit them to one another in some kind of connection.

09:08.960 --> 09:12.800
For there is altogether one fitness, harmony,

09:13.460 --> 09:20.000
and as the universe is made up out of all bodies to be such a body as it is,

09:20.700 --> 09:29.320
so out of all existing causes necessity, destiny, is made up to be such a cause as it is.

09:30.300 --> 09:35.000
And even those who are completely ignorant understand what I mean,

09:35.500 --> 09:41.520
for they say it, necessity, destiny, brought this to such a person.

09:42.520 --> 09:46.340
This then was brought and this was prescribed to him.

09:46.980 --> 09:52.100
Let us then receive these things as well as those which Aesculapius prescribes.

09:52.960 --> 09:58.600
Many, as a matter of course, even among his prescriptions, are disagreeable,

09:59.040 --> 10:01.520
but we accept them in the hope of health.

10:02.900 --> 10:09.220
Let the perfecting and accomplishment of the things which the common nature judges to be good

10:09.220 --> 10:13.760
be judged by thee to be of the same kind as thy health.

10:14.560 --> 10:22.600
And so accept everything which happens, even if it seem disagreeable, because it leads to this,

10:22.980 --> 10:29.500
to the health of the universe, and to the prosperity and felicity of Zeus, the universe.

10:30.360 --> 10:36.760
For he would not have brought on any man what he has brought, if it were not useful for the whole.

10:37.720 --> 10:44.660
Neither does the nature of anything, whatever it may be, cause anything which is not suitable

10:44.660 --> 10:47.080
to that which is directed by it.

10:47.700 --> 10:49.440
For two reasons then.

10:50.100 --> 10:53.860
It is right to be content with that which happens to thee.

10:54.820 --> 11:01.120
The one, because it was done for thee and prescribed for thee, and in a manner had

11:01.120 --> 11:07.320
reference to thee, originally from the most ancient causes spun with thy destiny.

11:08.220 --> 11:14.680
And the other, because even that which comes severly to every man is to the power which

11:14.680 --> 11:22.060
administers the universe a cause of felicity and perfection, nay, even of its very continuance.

11:22.960 --> 11:28.940
For the integrity of the whole is mutilated if thou cuttest off anything whatever from

11:28.940 --> 11:34.040
the conjunction and the continuity either of the parts or of the causes.

11:35.020 --> 11:40.860
And thou dost cut off, as far as it is in thy power, when thou art dissatisfied,

11:41.360 --> 11:45.160
and in a manner tryest to put anything out of the way.

11:46.800 --> 11:53.680
Be not disgusted, nor discouraged, nor dissatisfied, if thou dost not succeed

11:53.680 --> 11:56.940
in doing everything according to right principles.

11:57.680 --> 12:04.340
But when thou hast failed, return back again, and be content if the greater part

12:04.340 --> 12:08.060
of what thou doest is consistent with man's nature.

12:09.060 --> 12:16.060
And love this to which thou returnest, and do not return to philosophy as if she were a master,

12:16.600 --> 12:22.220
but act like those who have sore eyes and apply a bit of sponge and egg,

12:22.720 --> 12:27.280
or as another applies a plaster, or drenching with water.

12:27.900 --> 12:32.980
For thus thou wilt not fail to obey reason, and thou wilt repose in it.

12:33.580 --> 12:38.920
And remember that philosophy requires only the things which thy nature requires,

12:39.480 --> 12:43.260
but thou wouldst have something else which is not according to nature.

12:44.040 --> 12:49.560
It may be objected, why, what is more agreeable than this which I am doing?

12:50.440 --> 12:54.780
But is not this the very reason why pleasure deceives us?

12:55.620 --> 13:02.960
And consider if magnanimity, freedom, simplicity, equanimity, piety, are not more agreeable.

13:03.540 --> 13:09.020
For what is more agreeable than wisdom itself, when thou thinkest of the security,

13:09.320 --> 13:15.140
and the happy course of all things which depend on the faculty of understanding and knowledge?

13:16.980 --> 13:21.820
Things are in such a kind of envelopment that they have seemed to philosophers,

13:22.240 --> 13:27.080
not a few, nor those common philosophers, altogether unintelligible,

13:27.840 --> 13:31.800
nay, even to the Stoics themselves they seem difficult to understand.

13:32.740 --> 13:38.200
And all our ascent is changeable, for where is the man who never changes?

13:39.200 --> 13:44.920
Carry thy thoughts then to the objects themselves, and consider how short-lived they are,

13:44.920 --> 13:51.540
and worthless, and that they may be in the possession of a filthy wretch, or a whore, or a robber.

13:52.660 --> 13:58.980
Then turn to the morals of those who live with thee, and it is hardly possible to endure even

13:58.980 --> 14:04.660
the most agreeable of them, to say nothing of the man being hardly able to endure himself.

14:06.120 --> 14:13.620
In such darkness then, and dirt, and in so constant a flux, both of substance, and of time,

14:13.620 --> 14:21.300
and of motion, and of things moved, what there is worth being highly prized, or even an object

14:21.300 --> 14:30.200
of serious pursuit, I cannot imagine. But on the contrary, it is a man's duty to comfort himself,

14:30.660 --> 14:37.660
and to wait for the natural dissolution, and not to be vexed at the delay, but to rest in these

14:37.660 --> 14:45.240
principles only. The one that nothing will happen to me which is not conformable to the nature of

14:45.240 --> 14:53.420
the universe, and the other that it is in my power never to act contrary to my God and demon,

14:53.960 --> 14:57.560
for there is no man who will compel me to do this.

14:59.400 --> 15:06.580
About what am I now employing my own soul? On every occasion I must ask myself this question,

15:06.580 --> 15:13.540
and inquire, what have I now in this part of me which they call the ruling principle,

15:14.300 --> 15:21.480
and whose soul have I now, that of a child, or of a young man, or of a feeble woman,

15:22.100 --> 15:32.040
or of a tyrant, or of a domestic animal, or of a wild beast? What kind of things those are which

15:32.040 --> 15:39.180
appear good to the many, we may learn even from this. For if any man should conceive certain things

15:39.180 --> 15:47.920
as being really good, such as prudence, temperance, justice, fortitude, he would not after having first

15:47.920 --> 15:54.620
conceived these endure to listen to anything which should not be in harmony with what is really good.

15:55.460 --> 16:01.180
But if a man has first conceived as good the things which appear to the many to be good,

16:01.180 --> 16:07.580
he will listen and readily receive as very applicable that which was said by the comic

16:07.580 --> 16:15.480
writer. Thus even the many perceive the difference, for were it not so, this saying would not offend

16:15.480 --> 16:21.580
and would not be rejected in the first case, while we receive it when it is said of wealth

16:21.580 --> 16:30.200
and of the means which further luxury and fame, as said fitly and wittily. Go on then and ask

16:30.200 --> 16:36.520
if we should value and think those things to be good, to which after their first conception in

16:36.520 --> 16:43.840
the mind the words of the comic writer might be aptly applied, that he who has them through pure

16:43.840 --> 16:52.600
abundance has not a place to ease himself in. I am composed of the formal and the material,

16:53.320 --> 17:00.440
and neither of them will perish into nonexistence, as neither of them came into existence out of

17:00.440 --> 17:08.040
nonexistence. Every part of me then will be reduced by change into some part of the universe,

17:08.620 --> 17:16.820
and that again will change into another part of the universe, and so on forever. And by consequence

17:16.820 --> 17:24.380
such a change I too exist, and those who begot me, and so on forever in the other direction,

17:25.280 --> 17:31.740
for nothing hinders us from saying so, even if the universe is administered according to definite

17:31.740 --> 17:41.180
periods of revolution. Reason and the reasoning art, philosophy, are powers which are sufficient

17:41.180 --> 17:48.020
for themselves and for their own works. They move then from a first principle which is their own,

17:48.420 --> 17:54.440
and they make their way to the end which is proposed to them. And this is the reason why such

17:54.440 --> 18:03.520
acts are named kator thosais, or right acts, which word signifies that they proceed by the right road.

18:05.020 --> 18:13.120
None of these things ought to be called a man's, which do not belong to a man, as man. They are not

18:13.120 --> 18:19.980
required of a man, nor does man's nature promise them, nor are they the means of man's nature

18:19.980 --> 18:27.920
attaining its end. Neither then does the end of man lie in these things, nor yet that which aids

18:27.920 --> 18:33.500
to the accomplishment of this end, and that which aids toward this end is that which is good.

18:34.800 --> 18:41.800
Besides, if any of these things did belong to man, it would not be right for a man to despise them

18:41.800 --> 18:48.680
and to set himself against them, nor would a man be worthy of praise who showed that he did not

18:48.680 --> 18:56.040
want these things, nor would he who stinted himself in any of them be good, if indeed these things

18:56.040 --> 19:03.300
were good. But now the more of these things a man deprives himself of, or of other things like them,

19:03.300 --> 19:09.200
or even when he is deprived of any of them, the more patiently he endures the loss,

19:09.580 --> 19:12.620
just in the same degree he is a better man.

19:14.220 --> 19:22.440
Such as are thy habitual thoughts, such also will be the character of thy mind. For the soul is died

19:22.440 --> 19:30.200
by the thoughts. Die it then with a continuous series of such thoughts as these. For instance,

19:30.200 --> 19:36.660
that where a man can live, there he can also live well. But he must live in a palace.

19:37.420 --> 19:44.340
Well then, he can also live well in a palace. And again, consider that for whatever purpose

19:44.340 --> 19:51.300
each thing has been constituted. For this it has been constituted, and toward this it is carried,

19:52.040 --> 20:00.000
and its end is in that toward which it is carried. And where the end is, there also is the advantage

20:00.000 --> 20:06.260
and the good of each thing. Now the good for the reasonable animal is society,

20:07.080 --> 20:14.360
for that we are made for society has been shown above. Is it not plain that the inferior exist

20:14.360 --> 20:20.460
for the sake of the superior? But the things which have life are superior to those which have not

20:20.460 --> 20:28.420
life, and of those which have life the superior are those which have reason. To seek what is

20:28.420 --> 20:34.900
impossible is madness, and it is impossible that the bad should not do something of this kind.

20:35.920 --> 20:43.420
Nothing happens to any man which he is not formed by nature to bear. The same things happen to

20:43.420 --> 20:49.280
another, and either because he does not see that they have happened, or because he would show a

20:49.280 --> 20:56.860
great spirit, he is firm and remains unharmed. It is a shame then that ignorance and conceit

20:56.860 --> 21:05.160
should be stronger than wisdom. Things themselves touch not the soul, not in the least degree,

21:05.660 --> 21:12.980
nor have they admission to the soul, nor can they turn or move the soul. But the soul turns and

21:12.980 --> 21:20.720
moves itself alone, and whatever judgments it may think proper to make, such it makes for itself the

21:20.720 --> 21:28.580
things which present themselves to it. In one respect, man is the nearest thing to me, so far

21:28.580 --> 21:36.180
as I must do good to men and endure them. But so far as some men make themselves obstacles to my

21:36.180 --> 21:43.580
proper acts, man becomes to me one of the things which are indifferent, no less than the sun or wind

21:43.580 --> 21:51.140
or a wild beast. Now it is true that these may impede my action, but they are no impediments

21:51.140 --> 21:57.660
to my effects and disposition, which have the power of acting conditionally and changing.

21:58.300 --> 22:05.500
For the mind converts and changes every hindrance to its activity into an aid, and so that which

22:05.500 --> 22:12.560
is a hindrance is made a furtherance to an act, and that which is an obstacle on the road helps

22:12.560 --> 22:21.560
us on this road. Reverence that which is best in the universe, and this is that which makes use

22:21.560 --> 22:30.040
of all things and directs all things. And in like manner also, reverence that which is best in thyself,

22:30.480 --> 22:38.080
and this is of the same kind as that. For in thyself also, that which makes use of everything else

22:38.080 --> 22:47.580
is this, and thy life is directed by this. That which does no harm to the state, does no harm to

22:47.580 --> 22:55.060
the citizen. In the case of every appearance of harm, apply this rule. If the state is not harmed

22:55.060 --> 23:03.160
by this, neither am I harmed. But if the state is harmed, thou must not be angry with him who does

23:03.160 --> 23:12.440
harm to the state. Show him where his error is. Often think of the rapidity with which things pass

23:12.440 --> 23:19.300
by and disappear, both the things which are and the things which are produced. For substance is

23:19.300 --> 23:26.720
like a river in a continual flow, and the activities of things are in constant change, and the causes

23:26.720 --> 23:34.400
work in infinite varieties, and there is hardly anything which stands still. And consider this

23:34.400 --> 23:40.320
which is near to thee, this boundless abyss of the past and of the future, in which all things

23:40.320 --> 23:46.880
disappear. How then is he not a fool who is puffed up with such things, or plagued about them,

23:47.200 --> 23:53.820
or makes himself miserable? For they vex him only for a time, and a short time.

23:55.060 --> 24:02.360
Think of the universal substance, of which thou hast a very small portion, and of universal time,

24:02.940 --> 24:09.860
of which a short and indivisible interval has been assigned to thee, and of that which is fixed by

24:09.860 --> 24:18.740
destiny, and how small the part of it thou art. Does another do me wrong? Let him look to it.

24:18.740 --> 24:26.080
He has his own disposition, his own activity. I now have what the universal nature wills

24:26.080 --> 24:34.820
me to have, and I do what my nature now wills me to do. Let the part of thy soul which leads

24:34.820 --> 24:41.000
and governs be undisturbed by the movements in the flesh, whether of pleasure or of pain,

24:41.380 --> 24:47.720
and let it not unite with them, but let it circumscribe itself and limit those effects

24:47.720 --> 24:54.480
to their parts. But when these effects rise up to the mind by virtue of that other sympathy

24:54.480 --> 25:02.440
that naturally exists in a body which is all one, then thou must not strive to resist the sensation,

25:02.840 --> 25:10.000
for it is natural. But let not the ruling part of itself add to the sensation the opinion that it

25:10.000 --> 25:19.260
is either good or bad. Live with the gods. And he does live with the gods who constantly shows

25:19.260 --> 25:25.860
to them that his own soul is satisfied with that which is assigned to him, and that it does all

25:25.860 --> 25:32.780
that the demon wishes, which Zeus have given to every man for his guardian and guide, a portion

25:32.780 --> 25:41.800
of himself. And this is every man's understanding and reason. Art thou angry with him whose armpits

25:41.800 --> 25:50.620
stink? Art thou angry with him whose mouth smells foul? What good will this anger do thee? He has

25:50.620 --> 25:57.980
such a mouth. He has such armpits. It is necessary that such an emanation must come from such things.

25:58.600 --> 26:05.840
But the man has reason, it will be said, and he is able, if he takes pains, to discover wherein

26:05.840 --> 26:13.880
he offends. I wish thee well of thy discovery. Well then, and thou hast reason, by thy rational

26:13.880 --> 26:21.720
faculty, stir up his rational faculty, show him his error, admonish him. For if he listens,

26:21.720 --> 26:25.660
thou wilt cure him, and there is no need of anger.

26:28.000 --> 26:34.340
As thou intendest to live, when thou art gone out, so it is in thy power to live here.

26:34.900 --> 26:42.060
But if men do not permit thee, then get away out of life, yet so as if thou wert suffering no harm.

26:43.020 --> 26:49.300
The house is smoky, and I quit it. Why dost thou think that this is any trouble?

26:50.020 --> 26:57.800
But so long as nothing of the kind drives me out, I remain, am free, and no man shall hinder me from

26:57.800 --> 27:04.360
doing what I choose, and I choose to do what is according to the nature of the rational and social

27:04.360 --> 27:12.980
animal. The intelligence of the universe is social. Accordingly, it has made the inferior things for

27:12.980 --> 27:20.140
sake of the superior, and it has fitted the superior to one another. Thou seest how it has

27:20.140 --> 27:26.540
subordinated, coordinated, and assigned to everything its proper portion, and has brought

27:26.540 --> 27:34.620
together into concord with one another the things which are the best. How hast thou behaved hitherto

27:34.620 --> 27:42.220
to the gods, thy parents, brethren, children, teachers, to those who looked after thy infancy,

27:42.220 --> 27:51.160
to thy friends, kinsfolk, to thy slaves? Consider if thou hast hitherto behaved to all in such a way

27:51.160 --> 28:00.020
that this may be said of thee. Never has wronged a man in deed or word. And call to recollection

28:00.020 --> 28:06.540
both how many things thou hast passed through, and how many things thou hast been able to endure,

28:07.180 --> 28:14.140
and that the history of thy life is now complete, and thy service is ended, and how many beautiful

28:14.140 --> 28:21.260
things thou hast seen, and how many pleasures and pains thou hast despised, and how many things

28:21.260 --> 28:29.120
called honorable thou hast spurned, and to how many ill-minded folks thou hast shown a kind disposition.

28:30.320 --> 28:38.500
Why do unskilled and ignorant souls disturb him who has skill and knowledge? What soul then has

28:38.500 --> 28:45.540
skill and knowledge? That which knows beginning and end, and knows the reason which pervades all

28:45.540 --> 28:54.340
substance, and through all time by fixed periods administers the universe. Soon, very soon, thou

28:54.340 --> 29:02.920
wilt be ashes or a skeleton, and either a name or not even a name. But name is sound and echo,

29:03.340 --> 29:09.220
and the things which are much valued in life are empty and rotten and trifling, and like little

29:09.220 --> 29:15.740
dogs biting one another, and little children quarreling, laughing, and then straightway weeping.

29:16.560 --> 29:24.160
But fidelity and modesty and justice and truth are fled up to Olympus from the widespread earth.

29:24.340 --> 29:31.820
What then is there which still detains thee here, if the objects of sense are easily changed and

29:31.820 --> 29:38.000
never stand still, and the organs of perception are dull and easily receive false impressions,

29:38.360 --> 29:45.580
and the poor soul itself is an exhalation from blood? But to have good repute amid such a world

29:45.580 --> 29:51.620
as this is an empty thing. Why then dost thou not wait in tranquillity for thy end,

29:51.620 --> 29:57.820
whether it is extinction or removal to another state? And until that time comes,

29:58.360 --> 30:05.200
what is sufficient? Why, what else then to venerate the gods and bless them,

30:05.640 --> 30:13.240
and to do good to men, and to practice tolerance and self-restraint? But as to everything which

30:13.240 --> 30:20.240
is beyond the limits of the poor flesh and breath, to remember that this is neither thine nor in thy

30:20.240 --> 30:29.460
power. Thou canst pass thy life in an equable flow of happiness, if thou canst go by the right way,

30:29.800 --> 30:37.080
and think and act in the right way. These two things are common both to the soul of God,

30:37.560 --> 30:44.680
and to the soul of man, and to the soul of every rational being, not to be hindered by another,

30:45.610 --> 30:51.580
and to hold good to consist in the disposition to justice and the practice of it,

30:52.160 --> 30:56.120
and in this to let thy desire find its termination.

30:57.680 --> 31:04.840
If this is neither my own badness nor an effect of my own badness, and the commonwealth is not

31:04.840 --> 31:11.300
injured, why am I troubled about it? And what is the harm to the commonwealth?

31:12.480 --> 31:19.220
Do not be carried along inconsiderately by the appearance of things, but give help to all

31:19.220 --> 31:25.940
according to thy ability and their fitness, and if they should have sustained loss in matters which

31:25.940 --> 31:34.840
are indifferent, do not imagine this to be a damage, for it is a bad habit. But as the old man,

31:34.840 --> 31:41.620
when he went away, asked back his foster child's top, remembering that it was a top,

31:42.440 --> 31:50.440
so do thou in this case also. When thou art calling out on the rostra, hast thou forgotten,

31:50.680 --> 31:57.860
man, what these things are? Yes, but they are objects of great concern to these people.

31:57.860 --> 32:04.960
Wilt thou too then be made a fool for these things? I was once a fortunate man,

32:05.500 --> 32:12.840
but I lost it, I know not how. But fortunate means that a man has assigned to himself

32:12.840 --> 32:21.740
a good fortune, and a good fortune is good disposition of the soul, good emotions, good actions.

32:23.340 --> 32:25.000
End of chapter 5

